# Example test plan for lazyhttp
#
# A guided tour that goes green top-to-bottom with zero setup: log in and capture
# an access token, reuse it on the next request, run a full create → read → update
# → delete cycle, then echo a request back and assert on what the server received.
# Open it and hit "run from here" (a) on the first step, or run any step on its own.
#
# This file is also valid in the IntelliJ HTTP Client / VS Code REST Client.
#
#   dummyjson.com   a free, generous fake REST + auth API — no key, no rate limit.
#                   Logins return a real JWT; add/update/delete echo a result back.
#   httpbin.org     reflects the request as JSON, so we can assert on the method,
#                   query string, headers and body the server actually saw.
#
# Tip: {{vars}} are expanded in URLs, headers, bodies and the right-hand side of
# an @assert — so you can assert one response against a value captured earlier.
#
# Hosts and credentials come from http-client.env.json, so pick an environment:
#   lazyhttp --env dev example.http
# Only @product is defined inline below (it's request data, not environment).

@product = lazyhttp widget

### List the catalogue — also our reset anchor
### Marked with @reset: when it succeeds, lazyhttp clears every other step's
### result and drops captured variables, returning the plan to a clean slate.
# @group Setup
# @reset
# @name Reset state
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.products[0].id exists
GET {{api}}/products?limit=5
Accept: application/json

### Read one known product — capture its id for the CRUD section below
# @group Smoke
# @name Read product 1
# @capture id = json.id
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.id == 1
# @assert json.title contains Mascara
# @assert header.Content-Type contains json
GET {{api}}/products/1
Accept: application/json

### Search the catalogue
# @name Search products
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.total exists
# @assert json.products[0].id exists
GET {{api}}/products/search?q=phone
Accept: application/json

### Sign in via a shared, imported flow
### `# @import` splices in the steps of example.auth.http right here, as if they
### were pasted in — a reusable login kept in its own file. Its
### `# @capture token = …` populates {{token}} for every step below, and the
### imported "Log in" step is referenceable by name (see the next step). This is
### how you share one auth flow across many plans instead of copy-pasting it.
# @group Auth
# @import ./example.auth.http

### Reuse the login token with an inline response reference (VS Code syntax)
### {{Log in.response.body.$.accessToken}} reads the access token straight out of
### the "Log in" response directly above — the VS Code REST Client syntax.
###
### IMPORTANT: this reads "Log in"'s RESPONSE, so "Log in" must have already run in
### this session. Run "Log in" first, or "run from here" (a) from the top. Run this
### step on its own and the reference can't resolve — it stays literal as {{...}}
### and the server returns 401. The {{token}} capture (next step) has the same
### dependency. (VS Code needs a space-free @name to reference; lazyhttp accepts
### either, so referencing "Log in" works here.)
# @name Who am I (by response ref)
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.username == emilys
GET {{api}}/auth/me
Authorization: Bearer {{Log in.response.body.$.accessToken}}
Accept: application/json

### The same call the idiomatic lazyhttp way — reuse the captured {{token}}
### {{token}} was `# @capture`d on "Log in" above; it expands inside the Bearer
### header here. `# @capture` is preferred in lazyhttp and reads better in long
### chains — the response reference above exists for VS Code compatibility.
# @name Who am I
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.username == emilys
# @assert json.email contains dummyjson.com
GET {{api}}/auth/me
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}
Accept: application/json

### Create a product — capture the id the server assigns
# @group CRUD
# @name Create product
# @capture newId = json.id
# @capture createdTitle = json.title
# @assert status in 200,201
# @assert json.title == lazyhttp widget
# @assert json.id exists
# @assert json.price > 0
POST {{api}}/products/add
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "{{product}}",
  "price": 42.5,
  "category": "gadgets"
}

### Replace it wholesale (PUT), using the captured id
# @name Update product
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.title == lazyhttp widget v2
# @assert json.price == 39
PUT {{api}}/products/{{id}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "lazyhttp widget v2",
  "price": 39.0
}

### Tweak a single field (PATCH)
# @name Patch title
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.title == lazyhttp widget v3
PATCH {{api}}/products/{{id}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "lazyhttp widget v3"
}

### Delete it
# @name Delete product
# @assert status in 200,204
# @assert json.isDeleted == true
# @assert json.deletedOn exists
DELETE {{api}}/products/{{id}}

### Echo a POST and assert on what the server received
### httpbin reflects the method, query args, headers and parsed JSON body back.
### Dynamic variables ({{$uuid}}, {{$timestamp}}, {{$randomInt}}) are generated
### fresh on send, so we assert they arrived rather than on an exact value.
# @group Echo
# @name Echo round-trip
# @capture echoIp = json.origin
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.method == POST
# @assert json.args.team == lazy
# @assert json.headers.X-Demo == lazyhttp
# @assert json.headers.X-Correlation-Id matches ^[0-9a-f-]{36}$
# @assert json.json.ping == pong
# @assert json.json.nonce exists
POST {{bin}}/anything?team=lazy
Content-Type: application/json
X-Demo: lazyhttp
X-Correlation-Id: {{$uuid}}

{
  "ping": "pong",
  "sentAt": {{$timestamp}},
  "nonce": {{$randomInt 1000 9999}}
}

### Send a body loaded from a file, with {{vars}} expanded
### `<@ ./example.body.json` reads the file next to this plan and expands its
### {{vars}} before sending (use `< file` to send it verbatim instead). Toggle
### the request preview with `i` to see the resolved body.
# @name Body from file
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.json.title == lazyhttp widget
# @assert json.json.via == file-body
# @assert json.json.uuid exists
POST {{bin}}/anything
Content-Type: application/json

<@ ./example.body.json

### Catch a redirect instead of following it
### `# @no-redirect` returns the 3xx response itself, so we can assert on the
### status and Location header. `# @timeout 10 s` gives this one request a longer
### deadline than the shared 30s default would shorten (units: ms / s / m).
### Toggle the request preview (`i`) to see the active ⚙ settings line.
# @group Echo
# @name Redirect (not followed)
# @no-redirect
# @timeout 10 s
# @assert status == 302
# @assert header.Location == /anything
GET {{bin}}/redirect-to?url=/anything&status_code=302

### Stream the response body in as it arrives
### `# @stream` reads the body incrementally instead of waiting for the whole
### thing — watch httpbin emit ten newline-delimited JSON objects one by one in
### the response pane. The body is kept raw (streams aren't reformatted), and the
### assertion runs once the stream closes. The headline use is an LLM token
### stream — see examples/openrouter-stream.http.
# @group Streaming
# @name Streamed NDJSON
# @stream
# @assert status == 200
GET {{bin}}/stream/10

### Print everything captured so far
### IntelliJ treats this block as a comment, so the file stays valid there.
# @group Utilities
# @shell
# @name Echo captured values
# @assert status == 0
echo "Logged in as     : {{me}}"
echo "Operated on id   : {{id}}"
echo "New product id   : {{newId}}"
echo "Server titled it : {{createdTitle}}"
echo "Echo saw origin  : {{echoIp}}"
